EXPLORATION OF LOAN DATA FROM PROSPER

By Mai Nguyen

About: Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending platform that aims to connect people who need money with those people who have the money to invest. Dataset: The Prosper loan data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Our dataset consists of 81 variables with almost 114000 observations. The central question of this exploratory analysis is the relationship between different variables with whether the loan is completed or bad.

We will clean the data to address the problem of missing values in order to make it ready for analysis. Categorical variables and certain numerical variables with missing values will be left the same, and only the subset of data with no missing values will be taken into account when making exploratory plots. We now treat missing values of some numerical variables by replacing null values with appropriate values. After that, we move on to

#  We can see that there are 25 loans with missing BorrowerAPR. Borrower ARP is equal to Borrower Rate plus other fees. We calculate the borrower fees as the difference between APR and Rate, and add the median of borrower fees to Borrower Rate to fill in missing Borrower ARP values. 

df$borrower_fees <- df$BorrowerAPR - df$BorrowerRate

df$BorrowerAPR <- ifelse(is.na(df$BorrowerAPR), df$BorrowerRate + median(df$borrower_fees, na.rm = TRUE), df$BorrowerAPR)

# Fill in missing EstimatedEffectiveYield values. EstimatedEffectiveYield is equal to Borrower Rate minus some loss from fees. The approach is similar to filling in missing BorrowerAPR above.
df$estimated_loss_from_fees <- df$BorrowerRate - df$EstimatedEffectiveYield

df$EstimatedEffectiveYield <- ifelse(is.na(df$EstimatedEffectiveYield), df$BorrowerRate - median(df$estimated_loss_from_fees, na.rm = TRUE), df$EstimatedEffectiveYield)

# Fill in missing EstimatedLoss values by median values of estimated loss:
df$EstimatedLoss <- ifelse(is.na(df$EstimatedLoss), median(df$EstimatedLoss, na.rm = TRUE), df$EstimatedLoss)

# Fill in missing EstimatedReturn values by the difference between EstimatedEffectiveYield and EstimatedLoss:
df$EstimatedReturn <- ifelse(is.na(df$EstimatedReturn), df$EstimatedEffectiveYield - df$EstimatedLoss, df$EstimatedReturn)

# Fill in missing ProsperRating (numeric) and Prosper Score
df$ProsperRating..numeric.<-ifelse(is.na(df$ProsperRating..numeric.), median(df$ProsperRating..numeric., na.rm = TRUE), df$ProsperRating..numeric.)

df$ProsperScore <- ifelse(is.na(df$ProsperScore), median(df$ProsperScore, na.rm = TRUE), df$ProsperScore)

# We notice that missing DebtToRatio values exist in rows with unverifiable incomes. Calculate DebtToIncomeRatio for theses data points, adding $0.1 to account for $0/month incomes:
df$DebtToIncomeRatio <- ifelse(is.na(df$DebtToIncomeRatio), df$MonthlyLoanPayment / (df$StatedMonthlyIncome + 0.1), df$DebtToIncomeRatio)

To effectively answer the central question, we need to define completed and bad loans. For simplicity, we assume all the “Past Due”, “ChargedOff”, “FinalPaymentInProgress” and “Cancellation” loans as bad loans. We remove “Current loans” as there is no information to infer whether these loans will be completed or not. After that, we encode completed loans as 1, and bad loans as 0.

df <- subset(df, df$LoanStatus != "Current")

df$LoanStatus <- ifelse(df$LoanStatus == 'Completed', 1, 0)

Univariate Analysis

The structure of the dataset?

The processed dataset contains the data on 57361 loans with 2 statuses: Completed (66,37% of the loans) and Bad (33,63%).

The main features of interest in thr dataset?

The dependent variable in this analysis is the binary variable of Loan Status, whether the loan is completed or bad. I am interested in whether variables relating to financial information, credit history, credit score and loan characteristics can predict the loan status.

Other features in the dataset that will help support the
investigation into the feature(s) of interest?

Some variables that appear to have correlation with Loan Status from this univariate analysis are Borrower Rate, Deliquencies, Bankcard Utilization, Stated Monthly Income, Employment Status Duration. The correlation will be further explored explored in the Bivariate Exploratoty Plots section.

Any new variables created from existing variables in the dataset?

I transformed the categorical Loan Status variable into a binary variable with 1 representing completed loans and 0 representing bad loans.

Of the features investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I log-transformed the StatedMonthlyIncome, Debt to Income Ratio and AvailableBankcardCredit and limit the range of some variables that are skewed to the right. I also filled in missing values of some variables.

Any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I found a strong correlation between Borrower Rate and Prosper Rating, which is intuitive. Some variables that represent the same thing, such as CurrentDelinquencies and DelinquenciesLast7Years, or CreditSCoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper, Prosper Score and Prosper Rating have high correlation, so only one should be included in the model to avoid multicollinearity. Variables in the same group (Credit History, Credit Score, Financial Information) tend to have significant correlation with each other. Variables representing Credit History tend to correlate with those representing Credit Score.

What was the strongest relationship found?

The strongest relationship I found is the negative relationship between Credit Score and LoanStatus.

Reflection

The main question of interest when I explore this dataset is the relation between different variables to the probabilities of loan completion. Before conducting the exploratory analysis, I filled in missing values in certain columns. The first step is univariate analysis to understand the main variables of interest, including the depedent variable, Loan Status, and multiple independent variables in 4 main areas: Financial Information, Credit Score, Credit History and Loan Characteristics. The variables that are highly skewed are transformed using the log 10 base or limited to a certain range for better showing of the distribution.

Next, the bivariate plots aims to answer the central question of this analysis by investigating how different variables relate to loan status. The multivariate plots provide some visualizations on the strongest relationships in different categorical groups. We find the correlation independent variables and loan status are intuitive and in line with basic principles of credit management.
